Problem 1:

gcd function: gcd<-function(x,y){

gcd function returns the greatest common divisor for two input value

argument x is a double value

argument y is a double value

Return:the function greatest common divisor which is a double value

if any of x or y is equal to zero,none-integer, or negative values {print(ERROR)}

else if(x>y){

get the reminder r by r<-x%%y

while r!=0,substitute x by y, substitute y by r, and repeat r<-x%%y untill r==0

when r==0

Then function returns value of the final y, which is the greatest common divisor of x and y }

else if(y>x){

get the reminder r by r<-y%%x

while r!=0,substitute y by x, substitute x by r, and repeat r<-y%%x untill r==0

when r==0

Then function returns value of the final x, which is the greatest common divisor of x and y

}

The flow chart of gcd function is shown

Args:

Return: the greatest common divisor among 3 values

use gcd(gcd(a,b),c) to get the greatest common divisor of a,b,c

*if any of a,b,c is equal to 0,non-integer,or smaller than zero{print “ERROR”} }

Problem 2:

get_factors:

get_factors<-function(d){

get_factors return the prime factors of an input

argument d is a double value, dimension is null

Return: double values which are prime factors of input d

if d<0 or d is non-integer{ print(“ERROR”) }

else if d==1 { print(“No prime factors”) }

else if d is an even number (tested by d%%2==0){ create prime_factors which is a numeric vector and create o=3

while(d%%2==0), add 2 to prime_factors until d%%2!=0

if the remaining d==1 {return(prime_factors)}

else if the remaining d!=1{

While d!=1 {while d%%o==0 {add o to prime_factors and d<-d/o} o+2(to test the next odd number)}

eventually d would ==1, and when d==1, return(prime_factors) }}

else if d is an odd number(tested by d%%2!=0){

While d!=1 {while d%%o==0 {add o to prime_factors and d<-d/o} o+2(to test the next odd number)}

eventually d would ==1, and when d==1, return(prime_factors) }

}

is_prime function: is_prime<- function(e){

is_prime function is a vectorized function that returns TRUE or FALSE depending on wheather or not value is a prime number

Argument e: double, dimenison=null

return: double,dimension =null

create a logical vector prime_test

assign inputlength <- length(e)

assign length of prime_test = inputlength

assign g=1

while(g<=inputlength){ if e[g]is smaller than 2, or e[g] is a non-integer{prime_test[g]=FALSE} else{ create detect_prime<-length(get_factors(e[g]))

because prime number only has one prime factor, so

when detect_prime==1,then prime_test[g]=TRUE, when detect_prime!=1,then prime_test[g]=FALSE }

g+1 }

return(prime_test)

} The flow chart of is_prime function is shown
